{
  "query": "What are the documented benefits of retaining or restoring habitat connectivity for butterfly populations?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on documented studies, retaining or restoring habitat connectivity provides several benefits for butterfly populations. Studies found that restoring connectivity between habitat patches increased the abundance of Karner blue, high brown fritillary, small pearl-bordered fritillary, marsh fritillary and regal fritillary (action 3934). Well connected low quality habitat patches were more likely to retain Alcon large blue populations than less well connected patches, though connectivity did not affect occupancy of high quality patches (action 3832). Butterflies were more likely to move between connected habitat patches than unconnected patches, with common buckeye and variegated fritillary showing this pattern (action 3934). Common buckeye were more likely to colonize farther away habitat patches when released on corridors of suitable habitat compared to unsuitable habitat, though this effect was not observed when released close to habitat patches (action 3832). Grassland strips providing nectar or shelter resources were more likely to be used by butterfly species than strips with no resources (action 3934). Well connected cleared patches within woodland had similar butterfly species richness to isolated cleared patches (action 3832).",
  "action_ids": [
    "3832",
    "3934"
  ]
}

