{
  "query": "What management actions for traditional orchards and vineyards in the USA and Germany have been studied for their effects on butterflies and moths?",
  "relevant_summary": "Several management actions for traditional orchards and vineyards in the USA and Germany have been studied for their effects on butterflies and moths. For traditional orchards, one replicated site comparison study in Germany found that managed orchards had similar community composition and species richness of butterflies and burnet moths to abandoned orchards, but lower abundance compared to abandoned orchards (action 3917). In the USA, one controlled study found that an unmanaged and a partially managed orchard had greater species richness and diversity of leaf-eating arthropods (including caterpillars) than a commercially managed orchard (action 3917). For vineyard management, studies in the USA found that grass strips between vine rows had greater species richness of butterflies than the vine rows themselves, and vineyards managed to encourage native plants where insecticide was rarely used had greater abundance of butterflies than conventionally managed vineyards (action 3919). Additionally, vineyards managed with fewer chemicals had greater species richness of butterflies than conventionally managed vineyards (action 3919). Regarding chemical management, studies in the USA and Germany found that orchards, vineyards, and agricultural landscapes managed with less frequent, reduced or no pesticide, herbicide, fertilizer or chemical input had greater species richness of adult butterflies and moths compared to areas with more frequent or conventional chemical applications (action 3897). However, vineyards managed with reduced insecticide and herbicide application had similar species richness of moths to conventionally managed vineyards (action 3897).",
